<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<appendix xml:id="ap-lebesgue-integrability-criterion"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Lebesgue Criterion</title>

  <section xml:id="sec-lebesgue-integrability-criterion">
    <title>Lebesgue Integrability Criterion</title>

    <p>
      We record here a useful criterion for Riemann integrability that goes
      far beyond continuity and monotonicity. A proof can be found in
      <xref ref="biblio-bartle-sherbert"/>.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-measure-zero">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A set <m>A \subseteq \R</m> has <term>measure zero</term><idx>measure zero</idx>
          if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists a sequence of open
          intervals <m>(I_k)_{k=1}^{\infty}</m> such that
          <md>
            A \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty} I_k
            \qquad\text{and}\qquad
            \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} |I_k| \le \varepsilon,
          </md>
          where <m>|I_k|</m> denotes the length of <m>I_k</m>. A set of
          measure zero is also called a <term>null set</term><idx>null set</idx>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      A property is said to hold <term>almost everywhere</term><idx>almost everywhere</idx>
      on an interval if it fails only on a null set.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-naturals-null">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The set <m>\N</m> is a null set. Indeed, let
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. For each <m>k \in \N</m>, define
          <md>
            I_k=\left(k-\frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}},
            k+\frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}}\right).
          </md>
          Then <m>k \in I_k</m> for every <m>k</m>, so
          <m>\N \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty} I_k</m>. Also,
          <md>
            |I_k|=\frac{\varepsilon}{2^k},
          </md>
          and therefore
          <md>
            \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} |I_k|
            =
            \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \frac{\varepsilon}{2^k}
            =
            \varepsilon.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-countable-sets-null">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every countable subset of <m>\R</m> is a null set.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>A=\{a_1,a_2,\dots\}</m> be countably infinite. Given
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, put
          <md>
            I_k=\left(a_k-\frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}},
            a_k+\frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}}\right).
          </md>
          Then <m>A \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty} I_k</m> and
          <md>
            \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} |I_k|
            =
            \sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{\varepsilon}{2^k}
            =
            \varepsilon.
          </md>
          Finite sets are treated in the same way, by allowing all but
          finitely many intervals to be empty.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-union-two-null-sets">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The union of two null sets is null.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be null sets, and let
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. Choose open intervals <m>(I_k)</m>
          covering <m>A</m> with
          <md>
            \sum_{k=1}^{\infty}|I_k| \le \frac{\varepsilon}{2},
          </md>
          and open intervals <m>(J_k)</m> covering <m>B</m> with
          <md>
            \sum_{k=1}^{\infty}|J_k| \le \frac{\varepsilon}{2}.
          </md>
          Then the countable family consisting of all the intervals
          <m>I_k</m> and <m>J_k</m> covers <m>A \cup B</m>, and the total sum
          of their lengths is at most <m>\varepsilon</m>. Hence
          <m>A \cup B</m> is null.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-lebesgue-integrability-criterion">
      <title>Lebesgue Integrability Criterion</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A bounded function <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is Riemann
          integrable if and only if it is continuous almost everywhere on
          <m>[a,b]</m>; that is, if and only if the set of discontinuities of
          <m>f</m> has measure zero.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The Thomae function from <xref ref="eg-thomae-function"/> illustrates
      this criterion well: it is continuous at every irrational point and
      discontinuous at every rational point. Since <m>\Q</m> is countable,
      <xref ref="cor-countable-sets-null"/> shows that the set of
      discontinuities has measure zero, so the theorem predicts that the
      Thomae function is Riemann integrable.
    </p>

    <p>
      The criterion also gives a quick explanation for some earlier results.
      If <m>\phi</m> is continuous and <m>f</m> is integrable, then every
      discontinuity of <m>\phi \circ f</m> must already be a discontinuity of
      <m>f</m>, so <m>\phi \circ f</m> is integrable as well. Similarly, if
      <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are integrable, then every discontinuity of
      <m>fg</m> lies in the union of the discontinuity sets of <m>f</m> and
      <m>g</m>. By <xref ref="prop-union-two-null-sets"/>, that union has
      measure zero, so <m>fg</m> is integrable.
    </p>
  </section>
</appendix>
